i agree with another reviewer who said the book was unnecessarily long . genetic algorithms are a great programming tool , and there are some tips and tricks that can help your programs converge faster and more accurately , but this book had a lot of redundant information . if you are interested in using ga for solution-finding , i doubt you 'll find much useful in this book beyond the first chapter or so . many of the examples later in the book were so specific that i could n't see how they could be usefully generalized . really optimizing a ga approach for a specific problem domain takes a fair amount of tuning , and this book wo n't help much with that . i think time spent surfing siteseer or other publication sites would be better spent than reading this book .
